WEBVTT

00:33.090 --> 00:34.292
Welcome to the Well Community Church.

00:34.312 --> 00:35.633
So God, you're hanging out with us today.

00:35.674 --> 00:37.216
If we haven't met yet, my name's Brad.

00:37.316 --> 00:39.799
Get the privilege of handling God's word here this week.

00:39.819 --> 00:41.381
We will be continuing in our series.

00:41.401 --> 00:43.444
We'll be in first Samuel chapter 16.

00:43.985 --> 00:52.056
So to those at various venues and campuses, just so thankful for the various opportunities and locations we get to get together and walk through God's word.

00:52.076 --> 00:56.963
And the reason we spend time in the Bible, by the way, is here at the Well, we're just committed to the Scriptures.

00:57.003 --> 00:59.346
We believe it's inspired by God, profitable.

00:59.458 --> 01:02.121
for teaching reproof correction and training and righteousness.

01:02.181 --> 01:08.750
And so we read the Bible in hopes that the Bible might also read us and in so doing it might change us and shape us.

01:09.370 --> 01:11.413
It draws our attention to who our God is.

01:11.493 --> 01:16.019
We learn his character and what life is meant to be lived like under his authority.

01:16.039 --> 01:21.566
And so it's intended to sort of shape and mold us and even push on us a little bit.

01:21.606 --> 01:25.170
And so I hope today we can be both encouraged but also challenged

01:25.250 --> 01:26.612
as we look at chapter 16.

01:27.113 --> 01:35.366
We are continuing in a series called Monarchy where we're looking at the three monarchs of the United Kingdom, King Saul, King David, and King Solomon.

01:35.947 --> 01:41.576
And last week, if you weren't with us, we finished up at least what we're gonna cover in Saul's life.

01:42.237 --> 01:48.587
Saul continues on in the text, but we're gonna turn the page maybe literally here to King David.

01:48.627 --> 01:53.074
But last week with Saul, we talked about him being a king who finished poorly.

01:53.474 --> 01:58.479
And so he was a guy who, one of the perks of the kingdom, but he didn't want a relationship with the king.

01:59.159 --> 02:05.685
He wanted the blessings of God, but he didn't want personal obedience to God.

02:05.705 --> 02:07.187
And then we just made the observation.

02:07.247 --> 02:15.675
One of the things that's sad about Saul's life is you've probably all seen a Saul in your life or maybe seen Saul in you.

02:16.395 --> 02:23.442
And that is, he started making decisions and it just, it didn't take a rocket scientist to know that's gonna end poorly for you.

02:24.002 --> 02:40.088
And so it'd be really good if before then if you could confess and repent and soften your heart and turn to God because the decisions that you're making are gonna, you're gonna have to pay a price and people around you're gonna have to pay a price and he just couldn't do it.

02:40.669 --> 02:45.698
He just said such a hard hard, he could not confess, repent and yield to God.

02:46.559 --> 02:47.761
And so it cost him his kingdom.

02:48.242 --> 02:50.866
And as you recall from chapter 13, verse 14,

02:51.074 --> 02:53.076
It says, now saw your kingdom on a door.

02:53.116 --> 02:56.781
The Lord has sought for himself a man after his own heart.

02:56.921 --> 03:02.387
And so the Lord appointed him as a ruler over his people because you have not kept the commandments of the Lord.

03:02.427 --> 03:06.192
And so Saul's disobedience led to the kingdom being pulled away.

03:06.272 --> 03:11.738
And in chapter 15, we saw last week that says, the Lord has torn the kingdom of Israel from you today.

03:11.838 --> 03:15.703
And he has given it to your neighbor who is better than you.

03:15.723 --> 03:18.226
And boy, that must have stung a little bit.

03:18.562 --> 03:21.466
And all God wanted from Saul was repentance.

03:21.486 --> 03:23.469
He just wanted his obedience.

03:23.489 --> 03:24.371
He wanted his heart.

03:24.431 --> 03:35.647
And in fact, it's Psalm 51, which ironically is a psalm written by David after he sins and listen to what he says, and I think it would have been good if Saul would have heeded this.

03:36.348 --> 03:39.613
He says, for you do not delight in sacrifice, otherwise I would bring it.

03:39.633 --> 03:46.143
You are not pleased with burnt offerings, but the sacrifices of God are a broken spirit, a broken and contrite heart.

03:46.243 --> 03:48.306
Oh God, you will not despise.

03:48.450 --> 03:52.415
Oh, if Saul would have repented, it would have looked different, but he did not.

03:52.535 --> 03:58.683
And so, we continue now in the journey, bottom of chapter 15, verse 34, he and Samuel now part ways.

03:59.484 --> 04:16.306
Samuel now goes to Ramon, Saul goes to the house of Gibeah in Saul, and Samuel, verse 35, did not see Saul again until the day of his death, and Samuel is grieved now over Saul, and it says that the Lord regretted that he had made Saul king

04:16.610 --> 04:17.451
over Israel.

04:17.532 --> 04:25.625
And so now the king and the prophet role have now split and divided and God's going now in another direction.

04:25.745 --> 04:28.730
This week we're going to cover David a king after his own heart.

04:29.532 --> 04:34.921
After a brief period of mourning in verse 1, the Lord says to Samuel, how long now will you grieve over Saul?

04:35.582 --> 04:38.026
Since I have rejected him from being king over Israel.

04:38.527 --> 04:42.994
Fill your horn with oil and go and I will send you to Jesse the Bethlehemite

04:43.522 --> 04:48.448
For I have selected a king now for myself from among his sons."

04:48.608 --> 04:50.371
And so they're very practical way.

04:50.451 --> 04:52.193
God's like, hey, look, we got to reload, man.

04:52.633 --> 04:53.274
We got to move on.

04:53.334 --> 04:53.855
Next up.

04:54.035 --> 04:54.676
Okay, he's gone.

04:55.357 --> 04:56.999
It's time for us to appoint a new king.

04:57.580 --> 05:00.263
So, you know, get your little jar of oil, fill it up.

05:00.363 --> 05:02.766
Go see Jesse, the Bethlehemite.

05:02.806 --> 05:04.488
We'll talk about Bethlehem here in just a minute.

05:05.049 --> 05:06.411
And we're going to know one of his sons.

05:07.312 --> 05:10.376
And Samuel says in verse two and three, he's like, yeah, but it's not that easy.

05:10.436 --> 05:12.178
Saul's a little tweaked right now.

05:12.514 --> 05:14.937
And if he sees me, he's gonna kill me.

05:14.957 --> 05:19.463
Look at verse two, Sammy says, how can I go for if Saul hears him, but he will indeed kill me.

05:20.184 --> 05:22.246
And the Lord says, we'll just take an offering with you.

05:23.448 --> 05:25.690
Say that you're gonna go offer a sacrifice to the Lord.

05:26.171 --> 05:35.743
Say that you invited Jesse to the sacrifice and I will show you what you shall do and you will anoint for me one of them, the one whom rather I designate.

05:35.763 --> 05:38.907
So it's not necessarily dishonest, it's just not the whole truth.

05:39.488 --> 05:40.749
Is he gonna go offer a sacrifice?

05:40.909 --> 05:41.330
Yes.

05:41.634 --> 05:43.237
Is he going to invite Jesse and his sons?

05:43.597 --> 05:43.898
Yes.

05:44.699 --> 05:46.522
Is he going to also anoint the new king?

05:46.542 --> 05:47.604
Yes, but let's not share that.

05:47.765 --> 05:52.453
And so he takes off and he goes now to the house of Jesse.

05:52.974 --> 05:59.545
What's interesting about the house of Jesse is we're going to see a connection in Matthew chapter 1 in the genealogy of Jesus.

06:00.366 --> 06:02.450
It says that a guy named Salomon

06:02.850 --> 06:09.659
not to be confused with Sam and though it does sound funny to say, had a father or he was the father of Boaz by Rahab the harlot.

06:09.719 --> 06:20.133
Boaz was the father of Obid by Ruth the Moabite and Obid was the father of Jesse, who's ultimately the father of David who now is gonna be the king whom we annoyed.

06:20.674 --> 06:24.960
And so Samuel now did what the Lord said verse four and he comes to Bethlehem.

06:25.681 --> 06:31.168
And the elders of the city now come and they're trembling to meet him and they say, do you come in peace?

06:31.268 --> 06:32.530
Now he comes to Bethlehem

06:32.898 --> 06:35.241
Bet means house of, lechem means bread.

06:35.341 --> 06:38.264
So Bethlehem's namesake is the house of bread.

06:38.925 --> 06:58.766
Now that's interesting because several hundred years after now this event, Micah is gonna say that from Bethlehem will come forth now a ruler in Israel who's going forth are from long ago from the days of eternity speaking of course to Jesus who if you remember the birth narrative of Jesus, Jesus is born in Bethlehem.

06:59.327 --> 07:02.450
Which means technically speaking Jesus the bread of life

07:02.626 --> 07:07.472
is born in Bethlehem, the house of bread, and to nourish the world.

07:07.492 --> 07:12.838
And so Samuel now goes, as he was told, to Bethlehem to anoint now this king.

07:14.000 --> 07:17.664
The question now that we need to ask and answer is, why were the people afraid that he was coming?

07:17.985 --> 07:19.166
Does this not seem kind of strange?

07:19.427 --> 07:21.890
Like the elders of the city show up and are like, hey, are we good?

07:22.530 --> 07:23.492
Have you come in peace?

07:24.192 --> 07:28.818
Well, keep in mind his job, Samuel's, was to be a circuit writing judge.

07:29.122 --> 07:36.009
which means he went from city to city and he helped sort of adjudicate obedience versus disobedience.

07:36.029 --> 07:40.874
He helped to reprove, he helped rebuke if needed, he helped correct.

07:40.934 --> 07:45.899
And so he wasn't necessarily showing up like with really good news.

07:46.320 --> 07:49.603
He was usually showing up to say, this is right and this is wrong.

07:49.623 --> 07:51.866
So that could be why they're concerned.

07:52.546 --> 07:54.208
It also just could be that they respect him.

07:54.228 --> 07:56.050
Have you ever been around somebody you respect?

07:56.418 --> 07:57.659
You just act a little different.

07:57.680 --> 07:59.261
You clean the house a little different.

07:59.582 --> 08:02.445
If someone you respect is coming over, it could just be that.

08:03.086 --> 08:04.868
It could be just the tension in the land.

08:04.928 --> 08:06.450
Saul's a little tweaked.

08:06.470 --> 08:07.291
He spun out.

08:07.371 --> 08:09.193
Sammy is obviously fearing for his life.

08:09.574 --> 08:13.118
That might be the tone in the land that Saul's a little weird.

08:13.138 --> 08:14.620
Like don't get him angry kind of thing.

08:14.680 --> 08:17.663
Almost like living with an abusive person in your home.

08:17.703 --> 08:19.826
Or it could just be practical.

08:20.322 --> 08:26.611
I mean, in the very previous chapter, Samuel grabs a sword and hues Agag to pieces before the Lord.

08:26.771 --> 08:28.954
And so it could just be that, like, are we good?

08:29.515 --> 08:31.238
Or is this gonna be like Agag part two?

08:31.879 --> 08:45.458
And so sure enough, regardless, Jesse in verse five, and his sons are invited, Samuel says, I come in peace, I've come to sacrifice to the Lord, consecrate yourself, come with me, also now bring Jesse

08:45.698 --> 08:47.721
and his sons, they're invited as well.

08:47.741 --> 08:53.270
So you've got the elders of the city, Jesse, and all of his boys invited now.

08:53.991 --> 09:00.020
Now the reason I say that is they start with the oldest in verse six, and they bring the oldest before Samuel.

09:00.040 --> 09:01.001
Now this makes sense.

09:01.802 --> 09:08.653
The oldest according to the word of God in this culture would have gotten the blessing of the father and a double portion of the inheritance.

09:08.673 --> 09:14.642
So they bring Eliyav here before now Samuel, and it's like surely this is the one

09:14.754 --> 09:18.700
the Lord is gonna anoint, and on paper, that makes sense.

09:19.421 --> 09:27.432
But God doesn't always follow the cultural practices, and God sometimes takes things that look obvious on paper and just kind of switches it up.

09:28.113 --> 09:43.154
So we know that God chose Isaac instead of Ishmael, we know God chose Jacob over Esau, God chose Joseph over his brothers, and so it was very common for God to do that, which I'm thankful for, by the way, because Jesus says didn't come for the righteous,

09:43.394 --> 09:45.156
but the sinners who needed repentance.

09:45.176 --> 09:49.842
And I'm grateful for that because that means he came for me and obviously for you as well.

09:49.862 --> 09:55.770
And what he's gonna introduce us to is a principle through which now God is using to anoint this new king in verse seven.

09:56.130 --> 09:57.753
And it's looking at different metrics.

09:58.413 --> 10:05.683
In verse seven it says, the Lord said to Samuel, don't look now at the appearance or the height or stature because I have rejected him.

10:06.684 --> 10:11.250
For God does not see as man sees, for man looks at the outward appearance

10:11.554 --> 10:14.479
but the Lord looks at the heart.

10:14.499 --> 10:16.322
There's a different measuring stick here.

10:16.403 --> 10:26.521
Now, those of you who are NFL fans, we're just on the tail end of the NFL Combine season, which is a big deal for those who are wondering about their fantasy football team and this and that.

10:26.541 --> 10:29.586
And you've got now in the NFL Combine six events,

10:29.890 --> 10:32.576
that are recorded for these athletes.

10:32.596 --> 10:36.866
And it's used as a benchmark of measurement from even years past.

10:36.926 --> 10:38.530
And so it's a 40-yard dash.

10:38.610 --> 10:41.797
It's a bench press for reps of 225 pounds.

10:41.837 --> 10:43.842
It's a vertical jump, a broad jump.

10:43.862 --> 10:45.646
It's a shuttle drill and a three-cone drill.

10:45.947 --> 10:47.410
Who cares what they are?

10:47.650 --> 10:54.217
But their measurements by which this athlete and that athlete can be compared, not only this year, but for years previous.

10:54.317 --> 10:59.842
It's clear measurements of the one that will do well, supposedly, and the one who may not.

11:00.243 --> 11:02.946
Now, God, thankfully, has a different set of measurements.

11:03.586 --> 11:06.069
God isn't interested in your combined score.

11:06.489 --> 11:07.530
Man sees the outside.

11:07.590 --> 11:08.791
God sees the heart.

11:08.812 --> 11:11.654
You might write down 2 Chronicles 16, 9.

11:11.815 --> 11:15.218
It says that the eyes of the Lord move to and fro throughout the earth.

11:15.906 --> 11:23.955
that he might strongly support not those who have good combine scores, but that he might strongly support those whose hearts are completely his.

11:24.555 --> 11:27.619
God doesn't care if you're tall or short, if you're round or thin.

11:27.999 --> 11:30.722
God doesn't care if you've got hair on your head or coming out of your ears.

11:31.083 --> 11:33.405
God is interested in the heart.

11:34.086 --> 11:35.247
He wants the heart.

11:35.888 --> 11:40.253
In fact, Psalm 147 says he does not delight in the strength of horses.

11:40.613 --> 11:42.996
He does not take pleasure in the legs of men.

11:43.036 --> 11:45.298
The Lord favors those who fear him.

11:46.370 --> 11:47.992
those who wait for his loving kindness.

11:48.572 --> 11:54.198
And so we see now in verse eight, it wasn't the first son, and so now they bring Abinadab the second.

11:54.919 --> 11:59.324
And Abinadab comes before him, and the Lord says, not this one either.

11:59.444 --> 12:02.948
And in verse nine, they bring another, his name is Shema, not this one either.

12:03.008 --> 12:10.896
And in verse 10, they made seven sons now pass before Samuel, and Samuel said to Jesse, the Lord has not chosen these.

12:11.677 --> 12:12.818
So we've got a problem.

12:13.314 --> 12:17.600
I said, bring your sons, you brought your sons, and yet I'm 0 for 7.

12:18.702 --> 12:19.323
So what happened?

12:20.285 --> 12:23.149
And he says in verse 11, are these all your children?

12:23.770 --> 12:29.539
And you can almost sense Samuel kind of hesitating a little bit, or Jesse rather hesitating a little bit.

12:30.159 --> 12:32.343
And he goes, wow, I mean, there's one more.

12:32.363 --> 12:35.467
And he's out in the field.

12:36.209 --> 12:37.310
